-- BHP, David Jones, Graincorp, James Hardie, Perseus: Australia, N.Z. Stocks
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-09-20T06:34:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-20/bhp-david-jones-graincorp-james-hardie-perseus-australia-n-z-stocks.html

          
          
             Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index 
dropped 0.2 percent to 4,631.30 at the 4:10 p.m. close of
trading in Sydney. New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  advanced 0.2
percent to 3,216.94 at the 5 p.m. close in Wellington.  
 The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil for October delivery declined 1.2
percent to $73.66 a barrel in New York on Sept. 17, the lowest
settlement since Aug. 31.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), Australia’s biggest oil company
lost 0.3 percent to A$38.78.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU),
Australia’s second-largest oil and gas producer, slipped 0.4
percent to A$43.60.  
 Santos Ltd. (STO AU) fell 1.3 percent to A$12.93. New
Zealand Oil & Gas Ltd. (NZO NZ), that nation’s No. 1 publicly
traded explorer, dropped 1.5 percent to NZ$1.29.  
 U.S.-linked stocks: The Thomson Reuters/University of
Michigan preliminary September index of U.S. consumer confidence
unexpectedly fell to a one-year low.  
 James Hardie Industries  (JHX AU), the biggest seller of
home siding in the U.S., declined 1.6 percent to A$5.55.  Boral
Ltd.  (BLD AU), Australia’s largest seller of building materials
that gets about 13 percent of its sales from the U.S., dropped
0.6 percent to A$4.71.  
 David Jones Ltd.  (DJS AU) retreated 0.8 percent to A$5.20.
Australia’s second-largest department store chain was downgraded
to “underperform” from “neutral” at Credit Suisse Group AG.  
 Graincorp Ltd.  (GNC AU) fell 0.8 percent to A$7.56. Eastern
Australia’s largest grain handler had its rating cut to
“neutral” from “outperform” by analysts led by  Grant Saligari  at Credit Suisse Group AG.  
 Perseus Mining Ltd.  (PRU AU) jumped 8.3 percent to A$3.25.
The mineral exploration company was rated “buy” in new
coverage at UBS AG. Perseus and Adamus Resources Ltd. (ADU AU),
Australian gold companies with projects in West Africa, are
potential targets for larger producers looking for acquisitions
to grow, UBS said. Adamus shares surged 7.2 percent to 68
Australian cents.  
 Transfield Services Ltd.  (TSE AU) fell 1.1 percent to
A$3.69. Transfield, which provides maintenance services to
mining and infrastructure companies, was downgraded to
“neutral” from “buy” by analysts at UBS AG.  
